{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) has been designed to model time series prediction tasks and to serve sequential data over long time periods.",
    "For predicting student performance, as in Aljohani et al (2019 2021), LSTM can be helpful in capturing patterns in student data over time, such as throughout the course of a semester or academic year.",
    "Moreover, LSTMs can be trained on historical academic data (such as quizzes and test scores) to identify patterns and make predictions about students who are at risk of failure and future performance Brdesee et al (2022).",
    "The ability to learn long-term dependencies in the models that have used the LSTM architecture results in obtaining a high prediction accuracy of above 69.55% and up to 97%, and an average of 84.29% (see Figure 6).",
    "Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (Bi-LSTM), as an extension of LSTM, has the ability to capture both forward and backward dependencies in the sequential data which is useful for predicting student performance."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Moreover, LSTMs can be trained on historical academic data (such as quizzes and test scores) to identify patterns and make predictions about students who are at risk of failure and future performance Brdesee et al (2022)."
  ]
